Program Fun Walk & Run ‚ÄúLet‚Äôs Get Healthy Together‚Äù ini merupakan program larian amal yang dianjurkan oleh Persatuan Sukan Orang Pekak Negeri Kelantan (Kelantan Sports Association Of The Deaf- Kelsdeaf) Malaysia dalam usaha untuk mengeratkan hubungan dalam kalangan orang ramai dan golongan kelainan upaya. Disamping meningkatkan tahap kecergasan diri. Aktiviti larian ini juga dapat kita lihat semakin menular dikalangan masyakarat. Oleh yang demikian, kami telah mengambil satu inisiatif untuk menganjurkan satu larian 5km fun run bagi mengamalkan aktiviti kecergasan dikalangan anggota masyarakat dan pada masa yang sama mempromosikan aktiviti larian ini kepada masyarakat Kelantan.

 

 

Matlamat :-

Matlamat penganjuran larian ini adalah untuk mempromosikan aktiviti larian dan meningkatkan tahap kecergasan masyarakat. Selain itu, ia juga bertujuan untuk mendidik masyarakat untuk mengamalkan gaya hidup sihat dengan penyertaan aktif dalam aktiviti fizikal. . Pada masa yang sama, dapat meningkatkan kesedaran komuniti terhadap golongan kelainan upaya. Disamping itu juga, secara tidak langsung program ini dapat menambah dana / sumber kewangan Persatuan Sukan Orang Pekak Negeri Kelantan dalam menjayakan aktiviti-aktiviti serta Kejohanan Sukan Orang Pekak Malaysia Dan Sukan Orang Pekak Malaysia serta memberi hiburan kepada masyarakat setempat.

 

Objektif Program :-

1. Sebagai satu platform untuk mengumpul dana bagi membantu Persatuan Sukan Orang Pekak Negeri Kelantan.

 

2.Melahirkan masyarakat yang mempunyai tahap kecergasan yang tinggi.

 

3. Memberi peluang kepada masyarakat yang baharu mengikuti aktiviti larian.

 

4. Memberi kesedaran kepada masyarakat mengenai golongan OKU sebagai salah satu kumpulan minoriti dalam komuniti di Malaysia yang juga mempunyai hak sebagaimana individu normal.

 

5. Membina, memupuk dan melahirkan masyarakat yang kuat fizikal dan jati diri serta dapat mewujudkan sikap daya saing.

 

6. Mengeratkan hubungan silaturrahim dalam kalangan masyarakat.

 

7. Memberi pendedahan dan peluang kepada masyarakat untuk mengenali golongan OKU dengan lebih dekat.

                                      


SESI PENGAMBILAN RACE KIT:
i. Peserta TIDAK BOLEH mengambil race kit pada hari program berlangsung
ii. BAWA salinan kad pengenalan dan salinan resit pembayaran sebagai rujukan pihak krew program
iii. Peserta yang TIDAK DAPAT HADIR program larian perlu hadir berjumpa dengan pengurus program pada hari pengambilan race kit.
iv. Peserta yang TIDAK DAPAT HADIR tidak akan dikembalikan wang pada perserta.

Dear friends and colleagues around the world,

As we slowly emerge from the pandemic of the last 2 years, I am pleased to inform you that the APAO 2023 Congress is due to go ahead as a full face to face conference at the acclaimed Kuala Lumpur Convention Centre next to the world famous Petronas Twin Towers. Malaysia is no stranger to hosting major international Ophthalmology conferences and we welcome you once again to our beautiful country for a long overdue full congress of the APAO. Our theme for this conference is ‚ÄúReconnect and Collaborate‚Äù and I think that this is apt as we have been disconnected from each other for far too long.

Malaysia has fully opened its international borders on 1 April 2022 and is committed to hosting our international delegates in a safe and conducive matter with focus on ensuring the biological safety of our visitors. International flights from around the world to Malaysia are expected to increase in frequency in the coming months and I anticipate very few restrictions for fully vaccinated visitors to Malaysia.

The planning of the scientific and social program of the APAO Congress has already begun in full swing and all the ophthalmologists in Malaysia look forward to seeing you in February 2023. Please mark the dates in your diary for what promises to be an academically stimulating conference with lots of exciting social events and local tourism attractions for you and your families.
9a822074-8c44-427c-bbc0-4bbb99fe9df0.eventName: 38th Congress of the Asia Pacific Academy of Ophthalmology - APAO 2023

9cd31a09-6232-4702-a569-dc7e63324d2d.desc:
During the COVID-19 pandemic, virtual schooling was rapidly instituted. After two years of online lessons, students returned to school where assessments exposed erratic academic progress among students in the same class. Students struggled to stay attentive during virtual lessons while others were distracted by entertainment and social media. Social media engagement also impacted social interaction. Disparate access to the internet also hindered children from lower-income families from education. These situations have resulted in teenagers who refuse to attend school. This talk will focus on four cases of school refusal that are representative of the issues related to COVID-19.

-Ôªø-------

School Refusal ‚Äî From a Child Psychiatrist Perspective

A psychiatrist‚Äôs role in the management of a child or adolescent with school refusal or phobia comprises initial assessment, diagnosis of underlying mental health problems and comorbidities, and setting up a management plan with the involvement of relevant members of a multi-disciplinary team. The assessment would involve looking at the possible causative child, family, and school factors; deriving information from various sources for a working diagnosis leading to subsequent management plans. The use of medications where necessary in the treatment of underlying depressive illness in the child can be effective and beneficial. The psychiatrist can also play the useful role of a team leader or coordinator in a systemic approach in supporting the multidisciplinary team in working with the child‚Äôs family as well as school His or her privileged position also helps the team negotiate with the government educational department should such a need arise. Some vignettes of cases in local schools will be shared during the symposium as well as lessons learned from them.

Slow Dine, an experiential private dining event created by UNPLUG to celebrate local ingredients, real food and the sustainable way of life.

Inspired by provenance and sustainability, the Slow Dine features heritage recipes and aims to draw your attention to the entire local value chain from farm to table.

Homegrown Produce In this edition of Slow Dine, we are featuring the best produce from our friends at GK Organic Farm, which is located in Bangi, Selangor. They have been growing organic vegetables and fruits since 1994, using only their own compost. GK Organic Farm believes that the best food is as nature intended.

A Malay Heritage MenuThe Malay heritage varies throughout the country, mainly influenced by trade and migration from different cultures, such as Arab, Indian, Chinese, Siamese, Javanese and Minangkabau. In this edition of Slow Dine, we are showcasing the culture‚Äôs signature dishes as well as some of the lesser-known flavours from around the region.

cf279c69-b12a-494e-8347-1de28aae4c0e.desc:
Thirty years ‚Äì Towards a cleaner environment.

The World Renewable Energy Congress (WREC) and Network (WREN) is a non-profit company set up in 1990 to help foster the transfer of renewable energy technology from developed countries to developing countries.

For more than 10 years their Honorary President was The Deputy Director General of UNESCO, Prof Dr Adnan Badran.

WREC is a British Company which organizes conferences and seminars, publishes books, journals and magazines around the world in the field of Renewable Energy.

More than 45 countries have hosted the Congress, among them: UK, Germany, Italy, USA, UAE, Portugal, Bahrain, Australia, Romania, and Sweden.

The Congress participants have been from more than 90 countries.

Regional conferences have been held in: Italy, Canada, Colombia, Algeria, Kuwait, Bahrain, Malaysia, Zambia, Malawi, India, West Indies, Tunisia, Indonesia, Libya, Taiwan, UAE, Oman, Czech Republic, Germany, Australia, Poland, Netherlands, Thailand, South Korea, Iran, Syria, Saudi Arabia, Singapore, Morocco, Sweden, France, USA, China and the UK.

Among its eminent speakers have been H H Olafur Ragnar Grimsson, President of Iceland, Dr Romano Prodi, Prime Minister of Italy, Rt Hon Dr Stephen Timms MP, Rt Hon John Redwood MP, Rt Hon John Gummer MP, Sir Norman Foster, the Hon Sir Jonathon Porritt, Crown Prince Faisal of Jordan, H E Dr Abdulaziz Bin Othman Altwaijri ‚Äì Director General of ISESCO, (he is now WREN Honorary Chairman), Rt Hon US Secretary of Energy Hazel R. O‚ÄôLeary and US Secretary of Energy and Nobel Prize Laureate, Prof Steven Chu, Mrs Monika Ghandi, Minister of Environment, India, Admiral Truly, Dr Charly Gay and Dan Arvisu Directors General of NREL, USA, First Minister of Scotland Rt Hon Alex Salmond, President of Iceland Olafur Ragnar Grimsson and H R H Princess Victoria of Sweden. WREN worked with UN, UNESCO, WEC, UNIDO, UNEP, WMO, WHO, ESCWA, ISES, SER, EU, Common Wealth Science Council, and WB The Chairman of WREC is Professor Ali Sayigh, B Sc. AWP, DIC, PhD, FIE, FIEE, C Eng. Chairman IEI, UK member of WEC, and FRSA.

The first Congress was held in Reading, UK in 1990 and it has been held every second year since then.  In 2012 it was held in Denver where more than 3000 participants were present. WREN Created ‚ÄúAli Sayigh Trophy‚Äù to be given to the best country promoting renewable energy every two years. So far received by: Cyprus, Brazil, Italy, USA, Germany, France, Denmark, China and Morocco. The 2020 Congress was held in: Department of Civil Engineering and Architecture, Instituto Superior T√©cnico ‚Äì Lisbon, Portugal.
